A Republican strategy to counter Obama's re-election
The leaders of the Republicans justify their policies with the need to fight the electoral fraud.
However, the Brennan Center considers the latter to be a myth by affirming that the election fraud in the United States is less than the number of people killed by the lightning strike.
The Republicans' lawyers have, by the way, recorded only 300 cases of electoral fraud in the US in 10 years.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on voting.
In this sense, these measures partly undermine the US democratic system.
In contrast to Canada, the US states are responsible for the implementation of the elections in the individual states.
In this sense, since 2009, the majority of American governments have announced new laws that make the process of registration or the course of the course of the year difficult.
This phenomenon has gained in importance following the November 2010 elections, where 675 new Republican representatives were recorded in 26 countries.
As a result, 180 draft laws were introduced in 2011 alone, which restrict the exercise of the right to vote in 41 countries.
The new electoral laws require the voters to present a photo card and proof of US citizenship.
In addition, these laws also shorten the time-limits for the early vote, declare the right to register as a voter on the day of the election, and agree to the right of citizens to vote for which a court record is available.
Before the 2006 elections, no US state asked the voters to show a photo card.
Indiana was the first state to make such a claim.
The Supreme Court of the United States confirmed the constitutionality of the law of Indiana in 2008.
The Republican authorities hastened to extend this practice to other countries.
Over the last two years, they have supported draft laws in 34 states, which have forced the voters to show a photo card.
It is important to note that, in contrast to Quebec, the US citizens do not have a universal card such as the health insurance card.
In fact, 11% of US citizens, i.e. 21 million elective persons, do not have a photo card issued by a government authority in their state.
In addition, five million new voters in 2012 do not have such an ID.
However, more than a hundred dollars are often to be paid to get the necessary ID.
The new restrictions are disproportionately affected by young people, minorities and low-income people.
In fact, 25% of Afro-Americans, 15% of people with an income of less than $35,000, 18% of citizens over 65 and 20% of voters between 18 and 29 do not have the required photo ID.
This is even more important.
Students who are considered to be voters who are increasing their voice for democratic candidates are not allowed to use their photo card issued by their institution in several countries.
On the other hand, the same states allow members of fishing or hunting associations who are more likely to choose the Republican side to use the cards issued by these associations for election.
Before 2004, no state for the election required proof of citizenship.
Arizona was the first state to introduce such a claim.
Since 2011, a dozen states have adopted laws that require voters to prove their US citizenship.
These measures are clearly aimed at limiting the Spanish votes.
It is clear that two out of three Spanish voters prefer the democratic party.
In addition, in 2011, Republican legislators promoted laws in eight states that abolished the registration of voters on the day of the election.
In addition, you have limited the right of individuals and groups to provide help to those voters who want to register.
These restrictions are not without consequences.
For example, the electoral registration campaigns in the general elections in 2004 have helped to register about 10 million citizens.
The measures adopted since 2009 have reduced the share of new voters in 2010 by 17% compared to 2006.
In addition, the Republican legislators in five other states have adopted laws aimed at reducing the period for the early vote.
For example, in the 2008 general elections in Florida, 33% of the voters who voted in advance were African Americans, although they represent only 13% of the voters of the state.
The same applies to the Spanish population.
The latter represented only 11% of the voters, but 24% of the citizens who voted in advance.
In contrast, the white people, who represented 76% of the voters, represented only 46% of the voters who voted in advance.
Of course, the democratic legislators and their supporters have strongly opposed the adoption of laws that restrict the registration of voters.
Several draft laws were blocked by the veto of democratic governors.
The U.S. Attorney General has intervened to suspend the most controversial laws.
They could partially limit the damage.
For example, only 16 of the 34 states have adopted laws that require the display of a photo card.
However, the new rules introduced in 2012 will undoubtedly make the exercise of the right to vote more difficult.
The democratic critics denounce the party-political nature of the laws adopted and see in them as a clear objective the influence of the results in the countries that are crucial for 2012.
A report by the Brennan Center of 2011 shows that those States that have adopted these laws represent 171 of the 270 votes required in the electoral committee to win the Presidency.
It is too early to confirm with certainty that these changes to the legislation on the electoral system will have a significant impact on the outcome of the presidential elections in 2012.
But one thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on voting.
In this sense, these measures partly undermine the US democratic system.
