The Higgs Boson Analyses
The announcement of the likely discovery of the Higgs boson has aroused a certain amount of attention last summer, for good reason.
In fact, it is believed that this boson is involved in nothing less than the mechanism responsible for the mass of all objects in the universe.
And finally, it is the last particle whose existence was predicted by the standard model - our best or "least false" explanation of nature and the behaviour of matter, but not yet empirical.
But for the physicists it is not yet completely certain that it is really the Higgs.
We know without the shadow of a doubt that we have a real new particle, and that it is very similar to the Higgs boson predicted by the standard model.
In addition, this seems to be confirmed by new data presented this week at a major physics conference in Kyoto, but data is still missing to be completely safe about it.
However, let us assume that it is actually the Higgs, as there seems to be only a small risk of being wrong, and let's look at what it is.
There is a law in this world that is inevitably inevitable, which means that two objects cannot be present at the same time in the same place.
It is not possible to violate this rule - and do not try too hard because you will hurt yourself.
For even if particle physics is a really strange world, it turns out that it is also a law of this kind: the Pauli exclusion principle, which says that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time when they are in the same "quantum state," with this "state" in general being made up of some of their characteristics.
On the basis of this, the physicists divide the particles into two categories.
In a corner there are the good citizens, who are called fermiones, who are kind to the Pauli principle.
And in the other, the bosons, an evil band of anarchists, to whom nothing is sacred - certainly not this principle, which means that they can in fact be in the same place at the same time.
These bosons are divided into two groups according to the website The Particle Adventure from the Berkeley laboratories (which is absolutely amazing by the way): the mesons that we are not going to treat here and the "power particles," through which the great forces of nature spread and with which the Higgs boson would be somehow related.
But it must be stressed here that these bosons are not all so exotic creatures as one might think.
If you are able to read this chronicle, only thanks to a boson of extraordinary banality: the photon or the "light particle," which is the "messenger" of the electromagnetic force.
In fact, if a particle accelerates with an electric charge or changes the direction, the electromagnetic field is "disturbed" exactly at this place, like a pebble that was thrown into a pond.
This "interference" creates an electromagnetic wave (light, infrared or ultraviolet radiation, etc.), and this wave is nothing but a photon and thus one of the bosons "carrier of force."
Stable field
The same applies to the Higgs boson, with the difference that another field, the Higgs field, must be "disturbed" to show this boson.
However, the Higgs field is much more stable than the electromagnetic field; the pathogen must achieve very high energies, a little similar to a frozen pond whose surface could only be feared by a very large rock.
That is why a huge particle accelerator like CERN is required - the Large Hadron Collider is a ring with a range of 27 km! - to achieve such energies.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is again helpful to explain the relationship between the Higgs and the mass.
In fact, it is not all the particles and not all the materials that interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do this, but others do not - for example, a sheet of paper would never keep itself in the refrigerator.
And not all particles interact equally with the Higgs field: those who do it have a mass, while the others (like the photon, by the way) do not have a mass.
For what can all these research be "good," asks Mrs Plamondon?
For science, they are used to check the standard model (SM), and they also allow the physicists to carefully examine all the differences between the observations and the predictions of the SM.
There are, by the way, many physicists who are most eagerly hoping that such deviations will be found, as the slightest difference could open a door to a "new physics" and stop some holes of the model.
It must be said that the latter still has great shortcomings, as it does not provide an explanation for gravity (ups!) and the dark matter, which forms about 80% of the matter of the universe (again up!).
However, such deviations have not been found at CERN so far.
Impact
The impact of these research on the general population is more difficult to predict, but it would be wrong to assume that there were none.
By the way, in the early 1960s, the pioneers of the laser in the Bell laboratories did not suspect that their work would trigger such a revolution.
They saw scientific applications, but nothing else.
In fact, the late physicist Willard Boyle - who worked in the Bell Labs where the laser was invented in the 1960s, and who developed the first permanent laser (the first were pulsed) in 1962 - has already said that the laser was at the beginning considered a "laboratory play."
Imagine...
In addition, applications can also result from all the instruments that surround research.
For example, in 1969, Willard Boyle developed a small light sensor during his work in the optics.
Although it was not the original purpose, this sensor today serves all digital cameras worldwide as an "eye" and has introduced the Nobel Prize in Physics to it in 2009.
Of course, this does not mean that the activities of the LHC will necessarily change our lives, but it means that you really can never know...
Palliative care - the best way to die...
With her committee on "Death in dignity," Quebec has recently discussed the delicate issue of the end of life.
The debate will have to be resumed shortly, although a draft law is being prepared.
However, much remains to be done in this important area.
Le Devoir has tried to look at this more closely.
A few weeks ago, Mr. L. was living alone in his apartment in the Montérégie.
The prostate cancer that ate him had left him a period of two years.
"They gave me five years to live, I've managed seven years," he said half-hearted, lying in his bed in the home for palliative care of Victor-Gadbois in Beloeil, where he arrived the day before.
"However, it's always a shock, you can't be prepared for that," he says.
The disease is doing its job: an immeasurable weakness prevents him from going to the bathroom alone and even eating himself.
Sitting at the table in front of a delicious lunch, he agrees to let himself be helped with the food.
Brave he can even smile and talk to the strangers who are busy around him, bring him his medicine, and offer him a bath.
The courage of ordinary death.
"My greatest wish is to heal my diarrhea, as this is humiliating," he says.
A few hours later, the team found a cure for this evil.
"In the course of our lives we learn that a man is peeing standing," says Pierre Brodeur, a psychologist at the home of Victor-Gadbois.
Returning to the childhood phase is unacceptable humiliation for certain people.
"This depends on the person's ability to take a step back," he notes.
In the opinion of several people working in the palliative care, great events are taking place in the middle of these steps.
The patients who are enrolled in the home for palliative care Victor-Gadbois are all suffering from cancer.
They have a maximum life expectancy of three months.
At this stage, they are no longer covered by so-called "healing" care by the doctors and nurses who take care of them.
For Mrs A., 89 years old, the worst fear is to die "consciously and by suffocation."
But because of the disease, I really met my children.
"I have good children," she adds.
"I have no more wishes in life," she says, before she accepts that you put on a mask to help her breathe.
She still expects a last visit to her son, who comes from Italy, in the next few days.
In the home Victor-Gadbois you can offer a group of volunteers for body care and help with food intake.
The palliative care is used when there are no other options.
To make dying more pleasant.
In Quebec there is a bed for the palliative care of 11.700 people.
That's very little, considering that one day we'll all die.
Here life is continued under the best possible conditions, Dr. Christiane Martel, one of the doctors of the home.
Both at the level of physical, emotional or spiritual comfort.
The dying person is given oral care with Brandy or Pepsi, as desired.
Diabetics no longer need to control their blood sugar levels.
And death is part of everyday life.
Last night we served Mr. X a beer that died in the course of the night.
This morning his son will drink the beer at the feet of the deceased.
"We help family and patients alike," reports Nursing Director Nathalie Savard.
There is no day in the home of Victor-Gadbois.
In addition to an old man of 93 years, who enjoys the last family meeting in the yard and is well supported by his pillows, while being struck in his honor, a young man of 36 years, who is surrounded by his parents, his wife and his two little children, dies tragically after he has tried everything to survive.
"For six months, three to five beds have always been filled with cancer patients of less than 45 years of age," says Dr. Christiane Martel.
53% of patients enrolled in the Victor-Gadbois home come from their home, 47% come from the hospital.
The problem of access to palliative care
It is said that 77% of the Canadians do not have access to palliative care, that is to say, to a care that should ease the suffering of patients when the latter have reached the final stage of their lives, both at home, in hospital or in a nursing home.
And several organisations, such as the home of Victor-Gadbois and the society for domestic palliative care in the Grand Montreal area, are more or less exclusively specialized in the care of cancer patients.
It is precisely this great inadequacy in the health care of Quebec that makes several doctors specialised in palliative care look forward to the adoption of a law on the control of death aid and assisted suicide with concern.
Since October, a manifesto has been in circulation, signed by prominent Palliative Care personalities such as Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Lapointe to testify to their opposition to such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christiane Martel, the Quebec health system is not powerful enough to ensure that all are entitled to high-quality palliative care before one accepts to go to the aid.
Recently, she says, I saw a patient who was in the emergency room for 14 days with great pain, without taking any measures to relieve her.
I fear that patients will only want to die because they do not receive adequate health care.
And at the same time, several oncologists are treating their patients in spite of the worst forecasts.
The chances of survival of Hélène Richard were already minimal when she stopped a difficult chemotherapy.
When I told my oncologist that I was going to stop the treatment, she answered me that she was sorry to give up the fight, she told me.
But she told me I was finished!
No omnipotent care
Dr. Martel believes that 90% of the patients who have asked to die thank the care staff that they have not accepted this wish after their pain has been reduced by a team of palliative care.
It must be made clear, however, that palliative care is not omnipotent in the treatment of pain.
According to Elsie Monereau, head of the palliative care of the company of the home palliative care of the Grand Montreal area, 8% of patients do not respond to pain treatment.
At the very end of life, therefore, the doctors often use the terminal sedation, which leads to the patient to sleep either sporadic or permanent until the time of his death.
We can no longer pretend that we do not perceive this side of suffering.
Patients without pain relief will increasingly be able to use this terminal sedation.
Patients whose pain is not reduced say the same sentence: "I want to die."
But that doesn't necessarily mean, "I want you to get me to sleep," but "I want my pain to be reduced."
