In fact, the bitcoin invented by Satoshi Nakamoto (a pseudonym) is both a virtual currency (but can be converted into dollars, euro, etc.) and a protocol for the safe exchange such as BitTorrent, which allows the direct exchange of files.
With 15,000 computers on the network, about 200,000 transactions have already been recorded.
Some thousand websites accept bitcoin as a donation or as a means of payment.
After the price of bitcoin reached a maximum of 30 dollars (23 euros) in June 2011, it fell to 2 dollars five months later before recovering to about 10 dollars today (the courses are listed on the bitcoincharts.com website).
Nothing particularly impressive in comparison to the world trade in real currencies or financial products.
However, the European Central Bank (ECB) has shown interest in this in a report on virtual currencies published in October.
It describes bitcoin as "the virtual currency with the greatest success," "in competition with the dollar or euro" and "similar to the traditional currencies."
Bitcoin is different from other types of virtual currencies such as the "credits" used to make progress in a video game that you can win or buy (and sometimes exchange back) by playing.
The social network Facebook has also developed such a system.
However, the trade is controlled and processed each time by a central authority.
With bitcoin, all network nodes are simultaneously depositors of the accounting book, auditors, money issuers, as well as buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Each transaction between two users takes place in reality between two e-mail addresses in the form of an e-mail.
With the difference that the user can choose a different address for each payment, which ensures anonymity.
A number of data related to this transaction is electronically signed by a double encryption system.
In this way, the network can verify the authenticity of the transaction.
The content of the file will also make it possible to ensure that the traded bitcoins are present in the public accounts' accounts that are distributed throughout the network.
The decisive step is to enter this new transaction into this book.
This is done through a mathematical task that is started on the computers, with the winner, who is a kind of provisional central banker, who has the privilege of adding this additional line.
It is a file to be destroyed, i.e. the conversion of a large file into a shorter and clear electronic fingerprint.
The computers "take" the new transaction and add a number to it before the whole is "hacked."
The goal is to find the number that gives a special fingerprint (many zeros at the beginning).
When this number has been found, the other nodes can easily check if it is the right one.
The transaction is therefore permanently linked to the chain of all other transactions, and any modification would change the fingerprint.
If one user wants to pay with the same money twice (less than 10 minutes) with the same money, only one of the two transactions would be validated by the network and the other will remain without a link, as both have different fingerprints.
The computer that has solved the task receives 50 bitcoins.
In order to prevent inflation, this reward is regularly halved, probably before the end of 2012.
The bitcoins in circulation are therefore limited to 21 million, but can be divisible up to a hundred million, which leaves a certain margin...
In addition, the difficulty of the task is increased with any improvement in the calculation performance.
The life of the network has already had heights and depths.
The websites that provide services for bitcoin were attacked and the bitcoin deposits were stolen.
"The vulnerability used does not concern the actual protocol," explains Pierre Noizat, who has just introduced Paymium, which is a company for payment with real money and uses the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also reports on the possibilities of money laundering through this anonymous service.
However, cash also shows these shortcomings.
