They are accepted by others like the blog platform WordPress.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron from the Weizmann Institute in Israel analysed the accounting book and showed that almost 80% of the bitcoins are not in circulation.
In November, a "mega-sale" was launched.
"Thirty thousand dollars have been exchanged," says Jon Holmquist, who works for the company Coinabul, who converts bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Noizat, who is also the author of a book about this currency, firmly believes in the potential of this technology as a transaction network.
Its Paytunia system corresponds to a credit card (with real money) or a contactless payment with a mobile phone, but uses bitcoin to validate the transactions that are cheaper.
In addition, the holder manages his identity and can therefore remain anonymous.
The system can be easily implemented by the dealers, and the latter do not need to install new terminals or computer programs.
You just need to specify an address that can be "photographed and recognized" by a phone, Pierre Noizat says that he has thousands of users.
There is a general trend in which hierarchical systems are reconsidered in favour of more horizontal systems.
"It will take some time for Bitcoin to enforce, but 2013 could be a turning point," he predicts.
The ECB's report, by the way, provides for a reassessment of the various risks that are now considered to be high in the event of the success of this currency.
