A Constitution with the Scratch in Egypt
This is a new poker game by President Mohammed Mursi.
While Egypt, with regard to the Constitutional Declaration, which temporarily grants it the unlimited power of authority, remains more than ever divided, has decided to put everything on a map.
To surprise everyone on Wednesday, he announced that the Constitutional Assembly would adopt its final version the next day.
Just a week ago, the Head of State had granted this Assembly two additional months for the completion of his work.
Egypt has been based for almost two years now on a provisional text which has been amended several times, which weakens institutional stability and leads to legal confusion.
This new initiative has only made the country more divided.
For his opponents, the President remains in his "autocratic delirium" by continuing to "break his word" and "the right with his feet."
On the part of its supporters, it is assured that it is a way to end the institutional and political crisis as soon as possible and to speed up the transition process.
A referendum should be held within 14 days.
A very short period of time that forces the brothers to renounce their intention to explain the text section by section to the Egyptians.
It is also a way for the President to find his public and democratic legitimacy again, while the protest is raging all over the country.
After an interview with the American Weekend Time, Muhammad Mursi seems to be convinced that the Egyptians will be happy to vote.
In particular, as an ultimatum is put to the Egyptian people with this use of an overhasty vote: "Either you vote for my draft or I keep the unlimited power," the latter should probably end after the adoption of the Constitution.
85 to a large extent, Islamist members of this constitutional assembly adopted the text yesterday in a strange atmosphere.
The majority of the Liberals have not complied with the request.
Just before the Constitutional Declaration in mid-November, they turned away, as they believe that they were unable to make their views known.
Representatives of human rights organisations, religious minorities or civil society have acted equally.
In order to achieve the decision-making capacity, 11 people, deputy members, were added in all haste yesterday morning.
Some are very close to the Muslim brothers.
It is not surprising that the articles were usually adopted unanimously.
By the way, the commentators thought it was entertaining that the only difference of opinion of the day was expressed at the time of prayer, as some members of the panel considered that the pendulum of the constitutional assembly did not go very well.
The text, which was adopted last night, consists of 234 articles.
Article 2, which attracted all attention, remains the same as that of the 1971 Constitution and states that "the principles of the Sharia are the main source of justice."
The Salafist parties, for which the establishment of Islamic law is an important demand, had the hope to replace "the principles" with "the rules," which would have made a more strict application possible.
For the Islamists, the fact that this article has not been changed is proof of their good will and respect for the other members of Egyptian society.
The Liberals, who only see this as a propaganda attack, return "hypocrisy."
According to them, the Islamization of the Constitution is about other articles.
In particular, they have in mind Article 220, which gives an advisory function to the University of Al-Azhar, in particular with regard to the verification of compliance with the laws of the Sharia.
According to the Egyptian specialist Sophie Pommier, this is worrying because "the people who are invited to an opinion have not been elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
You can see the first signs of theocracy in this. "
The fears of the Liberals are also raised by the fact that the next rector of this university is likely to be much less moderate than the current one.
"At the moment, there is no concrete religious commitment.
With this constitution we remain within the framework of the bourgeois state.
Most lawyers who have worked on this text are not Ulema, but academics who have been trained in part in the French system, "says Alexis Brouet, who writes a thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
However, he acknowledges that "in relation to Article 220, there may be a ambiguity, as the terms used are rejected from the religious vocabulary.
In particular, it refers to the "Fiqh" [Islamic case law, Ann. d. Red.].
And in the future, the question could be raised as to the extent to which civil judges are competent to decide. "
In addition to his religious aspect, the text adopted yesterday is strongly criticised for the far-reaching powers it gives the President of the Republic.
The Muslim brothers argue that they are significantly reduced compared to the former regime.
Another point of dispute: the powers of the army.
In accordance with the military's wish, the examination of the defence budget is not presented to Parliament, but to a national defence council.
