"The Great and Powerful" leads to Moscow: Migrants save money for language
While Members and citizens are discussing the benefits of the law on mandatory language tests for migrants, criminals are already dealing with counterfeit certificates.
Every year 13 million guest workers come to Moscow, St. Petersburg and other cities of Russia.
Most of them are the citizens of Central Asia: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan and Turkmenistan.
Their only goal is to make money for the maintenance of the families that remain in their home country.
A law came into force on 1 December, according to which each migrant worker must take a test that certifies the knowledge of the Russian language.
To date, this scheme only applies to migrants who wish to work in the services sector, in the local housing sector and in the retail sector.
However, in the future, the tests will become a duty for all the host workers, according to the Federal Migration Authority.
It is not only language tests, but also tests in Russian history and the foundations of legislation that need to be done.
Language skills must be demonstrated for both the receipt and the extension of the work permit.
Exceptions apply only to citizens of countries in which Russian is the official language.
This law also excludes persons who have received their certificates and diplomas before the collapse of the USSR in 1991.
Sense, problem and protection of rights
The whole of the audit bodies will be under the aegis of the Pushkin Institute for the Russian language, the Russian University of the International Friendship, the Moscow State University, the St. Petersburg State University and other Russian universities.
The migrants can take the tests in all cities; already more than 160 appropriate centres have been opened in Russia.
The initiative to introduce the tests was supported by the members of the State Duma and the Federal Migration Authority.
However, before the law came into force in the press, civil rights people asked the following question several times: what is the point of the whole?
What changes does the requirement to have language skills, both for the Russians and for the host workers?
In particular, speakers from the Migration Authority responded to the question of reducing the number of forced workers.
"Many are now talking about the protection of the rights of migrant workers," says the Head of Representation of the Federal Migration Authority in Tajikistan, Viktor Severew.
However, their rights must be protected before they leave.
Only an organized recruitment will 90% solve the problems of foreign workers.
There are problems for migrants without work, education, language skills and medical attention.
Severew is convinced that a future migrant without language knowledge will inevitably meet people with evil intentions who put him under the pretext of help in a dark, tight barracks, where he will stay with dozens of his same months without food and documents and work 12 to 14 hours a day.
We get a lot of complaints from our migrants.
"In the home you are promised the One, and on arrival you will be betrayed, their passports will be taken away and will not receive the promised wage," confirms the head of the head of the labour migration administration of the Tajik Migration Authority, Tolib Schwaripov.
Don't scam, boss!
However, many citizens of the Central Asian republics, who want to make their money in Russia, admit that they cannot only control the language of the destination country, but can hardly express themselves in writing in their own language.
Of course, this is not so much their fault as the evil: only a few Turkmen, Usbeken and Tajiks can afford a reasonable primary education.
For in their families there is not even money to feed the children, let alone to buy them decent clothes, shoes and school stuff.
As a teenager, these children take the first chance to make money.
"It's difficult without language skills," they admit.
"You feel humiliated and inferior."
The following important aspect of the law is highlighted by the civil rights authorities.
Only migrants with legal status must take the test.
If you do not have this status, there is no examination and therefore no official work.
Meanwhile, most of the host workers remain illegally in Russia.
"Welcome" or "Access for unauthorised persons prohibited"
Many migrants confirm that it is not easy to get official status in Russia.
The reason is bureaucratic hurdles and, of course, the linguistic difficulties.
In addition, the legalization costs money: 12 to 16 thousand rubles.
A fake registration can be made quickly and only for a thousand and a half.
The staff of the Russian police know that our documents are largely fake and we are not registered, and that is why there are cases of extortion.
"They want one or two hundred rubles for cigarettes and tea," says the Tadschike Umed Hushkadamov to journalists.
"Just don't scare the cost of wrong papers"
The day the law came into force, it turned out that not only the registration documents of migrants can be falsified.
Some counterfeit certificates that certify the completion of the language test have already been confiscated by the Federal Migration Authority's staff.
The fake papers were printed with an ordinary color printer.
Of course, the new owners did not receive it for free: every migrant who hoped to save the tests in this way paid for the document seven thousand rubles.
This is more than twice the cost of the official test: it costs a migrant worker three thousand rubles.
The main direct task is to protect the system from corruption, so that the certificates cannot be easily bought, both officials and civil rights are agreed.
For the moment, the authorities can only promise to host workers who fall through the test the first time, that they will be given time for a language course.
In addition, new arrivals without language skills are offered places in areas where there is no need for active communication with people.
