On the second channel, illegal weapons are being stolen by criminals.
Baranez explains that this includes weapons stolen from both the police and directly from law enforcement staff.
Other weapons sold illegally are from military weapons camps.
In many military camps there were often explosions.
"There is evidence that some cases were arson to cover up the lack of weapons," says the former military member.
According to Baranez, arms manufacturers also contribute to the black market.
"Today, there are countless private arms factories that do not stand up to international competition and that is why the expert reports that the weapons are under-hand on the black market, for example in Moscow."
Another channel of the black market is the smuggling.
A lot of guns and guns come from poor countries like Kyrgyzstan.
"There is a production of its own, sometimes craft, as well as a mafia that organizes the smuggling," explains the former military member.
Where did the weapons come from?
Experts calculated the proportion of each of the five channels in the supply of illegal weapons to the black market.
In 2011, a report was prepared by the Centre for Problem Analysis and Public Administration.
The experts analysed reports of the Ministry of the Interior and the Federal Service for State Statistics, Criminological Literature and publicly available data on arms portals.
According to the investigators, the majority of the illegal weapons come from the army and the law enforcement authorities.
The report says that half of all weapons on the black market are there by "the blame of those responsible for their work on weapons."
According to the researchers, 17% of the weapons are from conflict areas, 14% are from theft in the production of weapons, and 5% are from illegal excavations.
A sales consultant of a weapons store that does not want to be named by name assures that for a long time now, no one has been buying weapons found in the event of illegal excavations because they are obsolete.
According to him, it is more common for traders to get the supply in a weapons camp.
