The skills are also to a certain extent comparable, but Germany is a state, that is to say, there are these Court of Auditors in the individual Länder - in that the German system is different from ours.
The BRH can only control federal funds, which is in line with our state resources.
Public funds, which are managed by the districts and municipalities, are subject to the control of the national accounts.
As far as German legislation is concerned, is it easier than ours?
In general, I would not like to compare this without specific information. Nevertheless, in some respects, Germany is often referred to as a model, but it is certainly not possible to say that Germany is better in everything.
Is that because the examiners are better there?
I'm not sure, but as I said, I don't like this kind of comparison.
It should also be noted that those countries that are a model for us also have problems.
Otherwise, they wouldn't have anything to do with working with our authority, would they?
As for Czech legislation, what was the importance for your authority of the revision of the procurement law, do you already feel any impact?
In view of the fact that this amendment is only in force for a short time, it has not yet had an effect on our tests.
As our controls take place afterwards, a certain delay has to be expected here.
So far, we are more likely to have an impact in the preparatory phase of future controls - so we have introduced the new control instrument "recognition of risks of inefficiency" and have examined and analysed with this almost 14,000 public contracts - the changes will of course have an effect here, as the thresholds change, the conditions for certain types of calls for tenders have been modified, among other things.
Do you see the adoption of this law as positive, or is the system being burdened with further bureaucracy?
I think that this law is definitely a step in the right direction and I hope that this adoption will be confirmed.
However, the problem may arise that the rules are "more stringent" and cannot be complied with.
Under the previous rules, the persons subject to an examination are already accountable to the institution (for example, in the case of an operational programme of regional policy, the Regional Council) to the effect that any failure to comply with the procurement law is equivalent to a breach of budgetary discipline.
But does it make sense to make the law even more stringent?
I do not think so.
The system must exclude those who want to attack and abuse the system and not punish those who have committed a formal error that does not affect the actual decision-making process.
Such a system only puts red tape under even greater pressure.
Where's the way out?
Let us first of all say what is not the way forward.
The Prime Minister recently said that the ODS would not involve the entrepreneurs with controls of the so-called "black system" - what exactly does that mean?
Is the black system now prohibited or allowed?
A law must have its validity, and if something is prohibited by law, then it is not easy for the President of the Government to come, and the Office of Control, whose duty is to control compliance with the law, is to prevent it from doing so.
He can say, "We change the law and allow the thing," but he can't say that we act like nothing was.
The procurement law contains relatively strict rules on the formal execution of certain transactions - and that is also right for the protection of public competition.
On the other hand, it is also tragic to exclude the bidder with the best offer only due to form errors.
The law will never be perfect, but it must be applied properly - and that is what I think is missing.
