We also cooperate with other personalities of the Czech cultural scene, which is related to the fact that we realize many charity events and concerts...
We are trying to get these people involved in our projects.
It has been shown that most are interested in working with us, and have fun with it.
What is the purpose of the results of the concerts against the end of the world?
For the establishment of the barrier-free education centre Studeo, where we have been working with the Tap Association at the Jedlička Institute for six years.
The students of the Jedlička Institute are regularly taken care of by readers who help them in different leisure activities.
As the students themselves do not have the means to visit the readers, we would like to help them in this way.
As part of the completion of the Jedlička Institute, a building of its own is to be created, in which we then move into with this project.
There are several groups and performers at each concert.
What criteria did you choose?
We wanted to put together a program that addresses all generations, including children.
In Prague, for example, Chinaski, support of Lesbians, Illustratosphere with Dan Bárta, The Tap Tap, Marián Bango and Jiří Suchý are performing.
You can find out everything else on the website www.kpks.cz.
Are similar "big events" planned for the future?
In May, we will be performing for the first time in the spring of Prague, and we will also prepare an interesting program with interesting guests for this concert.
Next year, we would also like to be in the Czech House in New York, and I personally - if we are in the United States - would like to connect this with performances in Washington and Chicago.
Your foreign plans are not very small, so far you have already performed in Madrid, Brussels, London or Moscow.
The Tap Tap is a group of people with disabilities.
How do you manage these trips in a logistical and organisational way?
It's not as bad as it seems at first sight.
Five of our members are wheelchair drivers, i.e. the wheelchairs must be transported in the luggage room. Furthermore, we must of course carry a lot of instrument bags and other luggage...
However, it has always worked out without any problems so far, ČSA and British Airways have always been very well prepared for us, that sometimes I have already wondered.
Even in Moscow, where we were recently, there were no problems.
Through your travel abroad, you have a comparison of what it looks like in the individual countries with accessibility, how to deal with disabled people, etc.
How have you experienced these things so far?
After Madrid, Luxembourg, London and other cities, where everything works better than we do, we were just in Russia witnessing that everything in the East is still in its beginnings.
Moscow is totally non-disabled compared to Prague. There it is still unusual when someone is travelling in the wheelchair alone in the city centre.
It is not even natural that a wheelchair driver, for example, is provided in the elevator.
Fortunately, there are also associations that are trying to draw attention to the problems of people with disabilities.
And in what way do we have to catch up with the more developed countries?
There are a lot of things that we're after...
However, it should be noted that an improvement in the situation still depends on the efforts of those concerned.
In London and Madrid, it is absolutely common for people with severe disabilities to move independently in public space, go to the museum, use toilets, etc.
But it is not very common for a larger group of disabled people to actively participate in the social event there, in which we are a little ahead of the West with the band The Tap Tap!
Respect in public and accessibility is one thing, but only when important athletes, artists, actors, politicians or lawyers come from our ranks will things really start to change.
So far, these are only individual cases of particularly strong personalities.
The Tap Tap is currently very popular, but if we go back a few years, what motivated you in 1998 to start a band?
At that time, I started as a maintainer at the Jedlička Institute, where I met many young people who were interested in dealing with something intense.
And since I am a musician myself and play saxophone among other things, I founded a music AG together with a colleague.
Well, over time, as our moderator, Láďa Angelovič, has been saying, something is out of control (laughs).
But did the band become known only in the last few years, or am I wrong?
It is true that the cooperation with well-known singers has helped us; in addition, we have also started to actively promote ourselves.
We have become aware that if you do something and you cannot see it outside, your own performance does not exist in a sense.
Thanks to the EU funding, we can also afford good readers, high-quality equipment and etc.
Was it your goal to get it this far with The Tap Tap?
From the very beginning, I felt the potential for dealing with things differently.
In the show business, one often copies the other.
This is logical in its way, as everything new is considered with caution and accepted only after a long time.
There are only a few really unique things, and I dare say that Tap Tap is one of them.
The first impression the viewer usually has is, of course, pity; that is only natural...
But this pity is absolutely unnecessary, because people with disabilities are not lonely and abandoned beings that we should regret.
They are people who can live and develop a full life if they have the means to do so.
I always say that if people with disabilities succeed, this is not just for themselves a progress, but for the whole of society.
Was it also helpful for this success that you are a strict boss, as you hear from many people?
If you want to do something good, you cannot compromise in many things and you must also demand a certain degree of discipline.
This is, in my opinion, quite normal.
Some come to us with romantic ideas, and when they find that they have a sample twice a week, have to complete preparatory phases and spend a lot of time on concert trips, then the enthusiasm of many quickly disappears.
But that's how it works everywhere, in any band that wants to work seriously and achieve something.
The Tap Tap currently has 20 members.
How many of them have been there since the beginning, i.e. since 1998?
Only one: Láďa Angelovič.
We're an open group, people come and go, you can't stop that.
Those who have the will and the desire to participate are always welcome to us.
