Poland and space.
Last week, Poland was accepted as the 20th member of the space authority at a Council of Ministers meeting of the Member States of the European Space Agency ESA. Poland is thus the second member country from the former Eastern bloc (to the Czech Republic, which became an ESA member on 12 November 2008).
Poland started close cooperation with ESA in 1994 and participated in several ESA projects in the following years.
The path of Poland to space, of course, began much earlier.
Even before the Second World War, Polish cosmos were concerned with space, and they did not always come to terms with it.
I would like to remind you, for example, of the presentation by A. Šternfeld of December 6, 1933 in the Warsaw Observatory, where the author presented thoughts from his pioneering work "Entrance to the Cosmonautik."
The ideas of the young engineer (born 1905), however, left the listeners cold, and after years, Šternfeld remembered that only Dr. Jan Gadomski had shown interest in his work.
In 1934, Šternfeld won the Prix REP-Hirsch, which was founded by Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch.
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) later became an important advocate of astronomy and space.
In Polish magazines he published hundreds of articles and wrote several books on these scientific disciplines.
Gadomsky's worldwide contribution to the development of space was appreciated, among other things, by the fact that one of the craters on the earth's side of the moon was named after him.
In 1925 a railway draisin was built in Poland, for which a rocket drive was planned.
Unfortunately, the author of the draft and the details of this project remained unknown.
It is not even clear whether the rocket should be used to start or brake the draisin.
The information on this is exclusively from the contemporary press.
In 1933, the Polish infantry began to deal with missile-powered fires.
The research was carried out by the Institute Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia in cooperation with Prof. Mieczyslaw Wolfke and Prof. Gustav Mokrzyckiegi.
It can be seen from the documents that the research was advanced to the stage of practical testing.
The research was then, of course, interrupted by the invasion of the German Wehrmacht.
In 1937, the technical press of the design of a photo-electric hunting dragon from Ing. Rohoziński showed up, and in the following year the work "Rakieta - torpeda powietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza" was published by the author Leliwa-Krzywobocky.
Both projects dealt with the military use of the missile drive.
Shortly before the war, all the projects for the military use of missile technology were coordinated by the Temporary Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasohy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy).
The Committee was set up in 1937, but after two years of work its work was completed from the start of the war.
Other articles on space were published after the war thanks to the work of the Polish Space Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne) in the Polish press.
The first mention of this company is made in 1954 in the November issue of the magazine Problem, in which four extensive articles are dedicated to space.
The article by Prof. M. Subotowicz contains the proposal to set up a space company.
At the time, there were the first projects on satellite technology, and it was to be expected that the research of space would have a future.
As early as 1956, the Polish space company PTA tried to join the International Federation of Space, which was founded in 1951, and in fact the PTA became a full member already in the autumn of 1956.
The following year, the first PTA chairman, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902-1959), became Vice-President of the International Federation of Space.
He was a member of the European Parliament until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, the PTA has been a major participant in the development of the highly successful meteorological missile (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), the first Polish rocket for scientific research.
The first type, the RM-1, was completed in 1957 and the first start was on October 10, 1958.
The rocket with a maximum flight height of 1800 m was about 80 cm long and did not weigh 5 kg.
Later an improved version, the RM-1A, was built, and in 1959 in the Błędów desert flight tests began with the two-stage rocket RM-2.
The rocket was 1.4 m long and weighed about 11.5 kg.
Another stage of development should already be able to do real scientific work - the RM-34 rocket should reach a flight height of up to 14.5 km and be used for the observation of high winds.
In 1962, however, the further development was stopped.
= = History = = The first RM-type missile was developed in 1962 to 1965.
The rocket was designed as a two-stage missile, its total length was 510 cm and the starting weight was 32.5 kg.
Three types of the missile were developed (meteor-1A, -1B and -1C), which were different in the size of the transport space for scientific instruments.
The Meteor-1A rocket had a transport room with 0.4 litres capacity, Meteor-1B over 0.34 litres and Meteor-1C over 0.62 litres.
The maximum flight height for all three types was 37 km.
In the years 1965 to 1968 the Meteor-2 missile was developed at the Aviation Institute, whose first flight tests began in October 1970.
Meteor-2 had a starting weight of 380 kg and was able to carry a payload of 10 kg to a height of about 60 km.
The Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 versions were then built.
It is also worth mentioning the accession of Poland to the Committee for Space Research in 1960, which was followed by the establishment of a national committee of COSPAR two years later.
Poland also participated in space research with Soviet satellites under the Intercosmos programme, and in 1978 the Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became the second Intercosmonaut after the Czech Vladimir Remek.
