In November 1979, a mob of demonstrating Islamic students occupied the American Embassy in Tehran and took 52 diplomats as hostages.
For their release, they called for the delivery of the fallen Shah Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, who had fled to the United States after the revolution, who had maintained the Patronate over his regime for decades.
For the American government there was no positive way out of this situation - it could not afford to throw the Shah overboard, as this would have greatly damaged the confidence of its allies in other countries.
At the same time, it was unable to enforce the release of the hostages in Iran, where the revolution led to the establishment of a theocratic regime.
It was a heavy blow to the call of the united states, and the subsequent fiasco in the violent attempt to liberate hostages only made things worse.
The diplomats were finally released after 444 days after negotiations had been negotiated by the Algerian government.
The fate of the hostages at home called for a wave of solidarity and anti-Iranian moods.
The debacle in Iran contributed significantly to the defeat of Jimmy Carters against Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential elections.
The film Argo of the director and actor Ben Affleck describes an episode of this story that gave the United States a small victory.
Six staff of the embassy were able to escape immediately before the embassies were occupied.
This ended after numerous complications in the residence of the Canadian ambassador.
The CIA, in cooperation with the Canadian authorities, managed to get the refugees out of Iran, helping them to cover up their true identity - they traveled with Canadian passports as members of a film staff who allegedly visited Drehorte in the country for a science fiction film.
Combination of the genres
The plan developed by the expert for "exfiltration," Tony Mendez, also required the cooperation of Hollywood.
To make the cover credible, articles about this film project appeared in specialist journals, press conferences were held, and the fictional production company had a real office.
The details of this operation have been kept secret for a long time. The film is based on the memories of Tony Mendez.
Affleck's film is a special combination of several film genres.
On the one hand, he is a realistic political thriller, but at the same time also a so-called "Caper Movie," i.e. the story of a successful Hussaar piece, such as the movie Ocean's Eleben.
This will change the mood levels in the film - on the one hand the documentary scenes from Tehran (iconic contemporary photographs are shown in the title sequence, and there are no big differences in the film version of the same situations).
On the other hand, the loose passages from Hollywood, which come ironically and slightly overstated.
And then there are the scenes from the CIA headquarters and other institutions - men in suits at the meeting table, on the offices, on the phone...
With this film, Ben Affleck has succeeded in a remarkable restart of his career.
A smiled actor has become a respectable director, and as an actor he is no longer the goal of ironic comments.
Argo is his third film after the Crimi No Children's Game (Gone Baby Gone, 2007) and the Thriller City without Grace (2010).
At the same time, it is Affleck's first film, which does not play in the director's home Boston.
The feeling for the atmosphere of the place was one of the features that the previous films of this director removed from the standard Hollywood.
However, Affleck also proves this feeling in Argo, where Tehran is "played" by Canada.
The best scenes of the film play in the streets and show the reconstruction of events that have really taken place - the initial sequence of the first storming of the message is very impressive in its clarity, and nevertheless conveys the feeling of confusion and unpredictability that occurs when the story moves somewhere.
A similar effect is achieved by Affleck with his team in fictional scenes (the wrong film team on a basar in Tehran).
Too much action in too many places
The director also had to deal with the fact that the story does not actually offer many exciting scenes in the film sense.
But with the little he works quite successfully, while sometimes he helps something in reality - which then doesn't always seem so elegant (the scenes in which the threatening crisis at the Tehran airport is turned away from a phone call in America, or also the persecution on the runway, seem a little bit curled).
The weakness of Argo is its too wide spread, which is due to the need to show too much action in too many places.
Alan Arkin and John Goodman are very charming in their roles as Hollywood staff, but their figures would have earned more space, and they are by no means alone in the film.
This makes Affleck's film lose a little bit of traction. It is a film that can be followed with some interest and that can be used to gold the design and the thriller of the 70's.
But it is difficult to see enthusiasm.
However, as a reminder of a piece of history that has been living in a certain way to this day and as proof of how overtaken the ideas of the almighty and all-knowing intelligence services are, it is sufficient.
