The house walls of Pompejis adorned a Latin graffiti over boredom, which dates back to the first century.
And then there's the question of how we actually define boredom.
John D. Eastwood, an associated professor of psychology at the University of York in Ontario, Canada, says that the problem is that boredom has been defined and discussed in many ways.
After a long reading of research literature and the presentation of the idea in front of a focus group of about 100 people, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues came to the conclusion that boredom can be defined as the experience of "wanting to do a satisfactory job, but not being able to do so."
As a result, boredom differs from apathy in that the person is not busy, but wants to be.
In the case of apathy, however, there is no need to do anything.
The key experience of boredom, he says, consists of a "disturbance of the attention process, coupled with a bad mood and the feeling that time is only slowly passing."
It makes boredom sound almost the same as depression.
But Professor Eastwood believes that although these two states may be related, bored people see the problem in their environment or in the world, while depressed people see the problem in themselves.
Sometimes we think we're bored, even if we're just having trouble concentrating.
In her study "The Uncommitted Mind: Defining Boredom in Terms of Attention" - for example: "The Inactive Mind: The definition of boredom from the point of view of attention," published in September in the "Perspectives on Psychological Science" magazine, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues point to an earlier experiment in which participants listened to a band where a person read a magazine article.
Some groups heard a loud TV program from the neighbouring room, which had nothing to do with the content. Others heard it on low volume, so it was hardly perceptible, while the third group did not hear these sounds at all.
The people who heard the barely audible television indicated that they felt more boredom than the other two groups - they had problems of concentrating, could not find a reason for it and attributed their difficulties to boredom.
When you try to focus on a difficult or exhausting task, the lack of attention can lead to boredom, says Mark J. Fenske, associated professor of neurosciences at the University of Guelph in Ontario and one of the authors of the study.
If, on the other hand, one-way activity is carried out - "like the search for defective products on a factory conveyor belt, music can distract and help not to feel bored."
In fact, he says, we now know that, often interpreted as a sign of boredom, we can even fight it by keeping people more attentive.
