But in general, teenagers are a pretty strained bunch.
In 1991, Reed Larson, professor of human and community development at the University of Illinois, conducted an experiment in which he contacted almost 400 teenagers and their parents seven to eight times a day with a pager.
He found that 32% of the young people were bored in the school and when they did the homework, while 23% indicated that they were bored when they were not in school.
But only 3% of parents indicated that they were bored.
Professor Larson says today, 21 years later, he does not know whether the percentage of boredom has increased or decreased.
He was, however, sure that "youth is felt to be particularly boring," mainly because children and teenagers have no major influence on their daily lives.
So back to my question of origin: Is boredom healthy?
Sometimes not, because in the extreme case, it results in people taking extreme physical risks and losing the gambling or drugs to ease them - that's what studies have shown.
On the other hand, many philosophers and authors are investigating the relationship between boredom and creativity. This opinion is Professor Vodanovich, who has been researching the subject for more than two decades.
"With boredom, the brain wants to tell you that something else should be done," said Gary Marcus, Professor of Psychology at the University of New York.
But the brain doesn't always know what to do best.
When you're bored and you use this energy to play and cook guitar, you get happy.
However, television can make it feel lucky in the short term, but it will disappear in the long term.
So if an iPad is enough for his bored child, it can be removed from the boredom. However, it has not learned to entertain or control itself, says Professor Fenske.
And he adds: "Self-control transmits from one situation to another."
The child not only learns to talk, but also gets more self-control in other areas.
I don't think we should celebrate boredom.
Nor should we be too critical of them.
Instead, our aim should be to feel well beyond the constant activity and technology guidance.
Professor Eastwood agrees.
"It sounds like we have to be bored more often, but boredom is the painful, unwavering desire to do something meaningful," he says.
He believes that in truth people are only looking for one way to turn off and relax.
"In an environment where we are constantly being overstimulated, it is difficult to get busy once the noise is stopped."
