For four euros, the carriers of the Indonesian volcano put their lives and health at risk when they carry 70 kilos of sulphur over the steep, stone paths.
There are people for whom their work is hell, and others are literally working in hell.
This is the case with Antoine Wijaya, one of the 400 mine workers who earn their lives by taking sulphur from the Kawah Ijen volcano in the east of the Indonesian island of Java.
For this purpose, he must go down to the bottom of his crater every day, where the sulphur-containing gas that flows out of the earth solidifies in contact with the air.
After he has broken out large sulphur stones that can weigh up to 70 kilos in total, he transports them in two bamboo baskets on his shoulders over the shredded paths of stone.
It is only 250 meters up to the top of the volcano, which rises up to a height of 2386 meters, but the exhausted carriers need more than 40 minutes for the rise in the tortoise, while keeping the balance and taking their steps carefully so that they do not slip and fall.
They know that every step can cost their lives, as it happened to a French tourist who crashed years ago on the steep slopes of the Kawah Ijen.
The mine workers of Kawah Ijen earn 5 euro cents for each kilo of sulphur that they dismantle.
At the top, they train the way between the tourists who photograph them like circus monkeys and run with the tiring heavy baskets three kilometers to the scale, which a mine company has set a little further down at a height of 1850 meters
The company is PT Candi Ngrimbi, who, since 1960, has been using the presence in the volcano and (never better) its workers, to whom it pays 662 Indonesian rupees (5 Euro cents) for each kilo of sulphur.
This is then sold for 10,000 rupees (83 Euro cents) to the petrochemical industry, because this mineral is widely used in everyday life and is used for the production of matches, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even for the bleaching of sugar.
"As we usually carry 70 kg, we get about 46,000 rupees (3,8 euros) for each way," explains Anto, who usually makes three routes a day.
For each route it takes three hours to complete it, but at the end of the day it has 138,000 rupees (11.5 Euro) together.
What looks like a miserable reward for such an inhumane effort is the triple of what he would earn with the field work.
"The daily wage of mine workers here, where 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros) are paid a day at the coffee farm and the average monthly income is two million rupees (167 euros), is very high," explains the carrier who previously worked as a wall on the tourist island of Bali.
There he earned 75,000 rupees (6.2 euros) a day, and the work was not so hard, but Anto returned with his family to Banyuwangi, a village nearby, for a reason that is as important as the sulphur in Indonesia: "I married a girl from Bali where they are Hindu, and I brought her to Java to convert her to Islam."
Anto has asthma, breathing with difficulty, coughing often and his eyes are irritated by the toxic gases.
The 27-year-old Anto has been risking his life on the Kawah Ijen for three years, whose sulphur has already left his first traces, although he covers his face with a mask and special glasses.
