Larry Hagman, whose role as the oil magnate J.R. Ewing in the television series "Dallas" is a symbol of the greed of the 1980s, is dead.
He was 81 years old.
Hagman, who came back this year as J.R. in a new season of "Dallas," died Friday afternoon due to cancer complications according to a family press release to The Associated Press by Warner Bros., producer of "Dallas."
"Larry was back in his beloved birth town of Dallas, where he played the iconic role he liked the most," said the family.
The family of Larry and his closest friends were in Dallas with him for the celebration of the Thanksgiving.
Linda Gray, who played the role of his wife in the original and follow-up series, was with Hagman when he died in the Dallas hospital, said her publicist Jeffrey Lane.
He made everyone happy who knew him.
He was creative, generous, funny, funny, loving and talented, and I will miss him very much.
"He was an original person and lived life in full swing," Gray said in a communication.
Hagman was diagnosed with cirrhosis in 1992, and he admitted that he had been drinking a lot for years.
In 1995, a malignant tumor was found in his liver, and he was undergoing a transplant.
